# Linux info
Daemons: a daemon in linux is a computer program that runs in the background without the need for 
user-input. Daemons are designed to perform various system level task and provide services with 
the need of direct user input like said. they are a fundamental part of the Linuz OS functionality, 
ensuring that essential services are always available.
Daemons are usually identified by having a d at the end of their name, such as: sshd, which would be the SSH daemon, 
crond. which would be the crontab schedular daemon etc. in modern Linux, daemons are managed by the init system like systemd, 
which handles their startup, shutdown, and monitoring. 

## Linux Commands

ls        # list all content in a dir
cd        # switches dir
ls -la    # list hidden files
echo      # output content
mv        # moves a file
cp        # copies files
locate    # finds files you name
grep      # pulls out the line
cut       # cuts a line (-d specifies delimiter)
wget      # file transfer command
ps aux    # displays all running processes on the system
mysql: this is used to connect to a mysql server/database. syntax is mysql -h <IP_ADDRESS> -u <USER> 
smbclient: to check share etc 


# Permissions
chmod +x         # add execute permission
chmod 777        # read, write, execute for all
chmod u+s        # assigns the (Set-User-ID)SUID on a file

# User Management
adduser          # adds user
cat /etc/passwd  # view users and UIDs
cat /etc/shadow  # view password hashes
su               # switch user

Permissions Format (ls -la):

  File/folder owner

  Group owner

  Others

  rw: read/write

  rwx: read/write/execute

   - = file, d = directory

üåê Network Commands

ifconfig       # view network info
iwconfig       # for wireless hacking
ping           # test connectivity
arp -a         # list IP and MAC address pairs
netstat -ano   # show open ports and connections
route          # display routing info

# cron/crontab
is a time based job scheduler in unix-like operating systems.
it automates the execution of taks at specific intervals

cronjob is used to manage cron


# Installing Tools & Starting Services

apt-get install <tool>               # install tools
service apache2 start               # start Apache web server
service postgresql start            # start PostgreSQL
systemctl enable ssh                # enable SSH
systemctl enable postgresql         # start PostgreSQL at boot
python3 -m http.server 80           # start Python web server


